  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can I prepare for GRE in 20 days?",
  "response": "Preparing for the GRE in 20 days is a daunting task, but with a focused and disciplined approach, it can be done. Here\u2019s a comprehensive plan to help you maximize your preparation:\n\n1. **Assess Your Current Level:**\n   - Take a full-length practice test to understand your strengths and weaknesses. Use this as a benchmark for your progress.\n\n2. **Set a Target Score:**\n   - Determine a realistic target score based on the requirements of your target graduate programs.\n\n3. **Create a Study Schedule:**\n   - Divide the 20 days into specific periods dedicated to different sections: Verbal Reasoning, Quantitative Reasoning, and Analytical Writing.\n   - Plan for 4-6 hours of focused study each day, broken into smaller sessions to maintain focus.\n\n4. **Focus on Weaknesses:**\n   - Prioritize topics that need the most improvement. Allocate more time to these areas while maintaining a balance with your strengths.\n\n5. **Verbal Reasoning Preparation:**\n   - **Vocabulary:** Study high-frequency GRE words. Use flashcards or apps like Anki for regular review.\n   - **Reading Comprehension:** Practice with diverse texts to improve understanding and speed.\n   - **Practice Questions:** Use GRE prep books and online resources to practice sentence equivalence and text completion questions.\n\n6. **Quantitative Reasoning Preparation:**\n   - **Review Fundamentals:** Brush up on basic arithmetic, algebra, geometry, and data analysis.\n   - **Practice Problem-Solving:** Work on a variety of quantitative questions daily.\n   - **Advanced Topics:** If time allows, address more complex topics, such as probability and advanced algebra.\n\n7. **Analytical Writing Preparation:**\n   - **Understand the Tasks:** Familiarize yourself with the issue and argument tasks.\n   - **Practice Writing:** Write at least a few practice essays. Focus on structure, clarity, and argument development.\n   - **Review Sample Essays:** Analyze high-scoring sample essays to understand what is expected.\n\n8. **Time Management:**\n   - Practice pacing by doing timed drills for each section.\n   - Gradually increase the difficulty and length of practice sessions.\n\n9. **Review Mistakes:**\n   - After practice tests or questions, thoroughly review your errors to understand where you went wrong and how to correct it.\n\n10. **Utilize Official Resources:**\n    - Use official GRE materials from ETS as they closely mimic the actual test experience.\n\n11. **Stay Healthy:**\n    - Ensure you get adequate sleep, maintain a balanced diet, and exercise regularly to keep your mind sharp.\n\n12. **Mock Tests:**\n    - Take at least 2-3 full-length practice tests under test conditions to track your progress and build stamina.\n\n13. **Final Review:**\n    - In the last few days, consolidate your knowledge and review important strategies and concepts.\n\n14. **Test-Day Strategy:**\n    - Familiarize yourself with the test center logistics and ensure you have all necessary materials ready for test day.\n\nBy sticking to this structured plan and staying committed, you can improve your skills and enhance your confidence in taking the GRE.",
